[[File:Yamazaki Ansai.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Yamazaki Ansai]] '''Suika Shintō''' (垂加神道, Suika Shintō) is a Shintō doctrine proposed by [[Yamazaki Ansai]] in the early [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]]. It is considered one of the schools of [[Confucian Shintō]], alongside [[Yoshikawa Shintō]] and [[Ise faith|Ise Shintō]].<ref name="yougo1">{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=National History Education Research Council|title=Japanese History B Terminology Collection―with A Notes|year=2009|edition=Revised Edition|publisher=[[Yamakawa Publishing]]}}</ref> It is also said to be related to studies of the [[Nihon Shoki]].<ref>{{Cite web|lang=ja|url=https://allreviews.jp/review/5126|title=The Birth of Nihon Shoki: The History of Compilation and Reception (Yagi Shoten) - Edited by Keita Endo, Haruhito Kawachi, Atsushi Sekine, Hiroshi Hosoi - Excerpts by Haruhito Kawachi|publisher=ALL REVIEWS|date=2020-11-18|accessdate=2021-01-03}}</ref>
== Overview ==
Suika Shintō is a comprehensive form of Shintō developed by Yamazaki Ansai, who studied various Shintō doctrines, including Yoshikawa Shintō. He further refined these teachings by incorporating elements of [[Zhu Xi Confucianism]], [[Onmyōdō]], and [[:en:I Ching|Yi Studies]], creating a doctrine deeply rooted in morality.<ref name="yougo1" />
=== Origin of the Name "Suika" === Originally a [[Rinzai school]] monk, Yamazaki Ansai later studied [[Confucianism]] but found it insufficient. He subsequently learned [[Ise faith|Ise Shintō]] from [[Watarai Nobuyoshi]] (also known as Deguchi Nobuyoshi) and [[Ōnakatomi no Masanaga]] (also known as Kawabe no Masanaga). Ansai later apprenticed under [[Yoshikawa Koretari]] and mastered the esoteric teachings of Yoshikawa Shintō. The name "Suika" was bestowed upon Ansai by Koretari at that time. It originates from a phrase in the ''{{ill|Yamatohime-no-mikoto Seiki|en|倭姫命世記|1=Yamatohime no Mikoto Seiki|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamatohime-no-mikoto Seiki|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamatohime no Mikoto Seiki|qq=}}'' that states, "神垂以祈祷為先冥加以正直以本" ("The divine descends; prayer comes first; blessings arise from uprightness and sincerity").
=== Philosophy === Suika Shintō defines Shintō as the way in which the [[:en:Emperor of Japan|Emperor]], as a descendant of the [[Amaterasu|Sun Go'''Suika Shinto'''
ess]], governs under her divine will. It emphasizes reverence for the Emperor and advocates the unification of Shintō and Confucianism, leading to the rise of {{ill|sonnō thought|en|尊王思想|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/sonnō thought|qq=}} (reverence for the emperor).<ref name="yougo2">{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Japanese History Terminology Study Group|title=Essential Japanese History Terms|year=2009|edition=4th Edition|publisher=[[Jikkyo Publishing]]}}</ref>
The philosophy places utmost importance on the human virtue of "reverence" (敬). Ansai taught that by fully embodying reverence, humans could achieve unity with heaven and earth ("the unity of heaven and man"). He defined "reverence in action" as "uprightness" (正直).<ref name="itou">{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Satoshi Itō|title=What is Shintō?|year=2012|series=[[Chūkō Shinsho]]|publisher=[[Chūōkōron-shinsha]]}}</ref>
=== Influence === Due to its emphasis on reverence for the Emperor, Suika Shintō became the ideological backbone of [[sonnō thought]] and greatly influenced the [[Mito School]]'s reverence for the Emperor, as well as [[nationalism]] and [[ultranationalism]].<ref name="yougo2" /> Figures such as {{ill|Takenouchi Keiji|en|竹内敬持|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takenouchi Keiji|qq=}} and {{ill|Yamagata Daini|en|山県大弐|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamagata Daini|qq=}} emerged as fervent imperial loyalists from this tradition. Similarly, {{ill|Asami Keisai|en|浅見絅斎|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Asami Keisai|qq=}} advocated for reverence for the Emperor through Confucian theories of moral obligation. These developments eventually contributed to the flourishing of {{ill|Nativism (Japan)|en|日本主義|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nativism (Japan)|qq=}} and [[kokugaku]] studies.
